ions, rivalries, and occasional cooperation between the two blocs, with essays that represent the cutting edge of Cold War Studies and analyze aesthetic preferences and cultural phenomena as various as interior design in East and West Germany; the Soviet stance on genetics; US cultural diplomacy during and after the Cold War; and the role of popular music as the universal cultural ambassador. An illuminating and wide-ranging survey of interrelated collective dreams from both sides of the Iron Curtain, Divided Dreamworlds? has a place on the bookshelf of any modern historian.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAbrams, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBugajski, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeJong-Lambert, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJampol, Justinian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangenkamp, Harm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMihelj, Sabina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomijn, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomijn, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aScholz, Natalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott-Smith, Giles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScott-Smith, Giles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSegal, Joes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSegal, Joes, 